{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b2618bb8-295c-43ea-a891-bcee3faceb7e","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed. Look here:\n\n**User-level crashes:**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\n**System-level crashes:**\n```\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nCrash reports are `.ips` files (JSON format). Find your app's report with:\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- Reports may take a few seconds to appear after a crash.\n- You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n- The `.ips` file contains the full native backtrace, exception type (`EXC_BAD_ACCESS`, `SIGABRT`, etc.), and register state.\n\nIf you need to **symbolicate** the .NET runtime frames in that `.ips` file, let me know — I can help with that too.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"31d81b2f-b2e6-43f7-a1a1-b3aceea6e456","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to search the codebase or use tools for this.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files) in specific locations. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":335,"requestId":"AC03:EB431:13DD454:1647B92:6A067165"},"id":"27762a60-2791-45f6-b6ee-7451caec6fc0","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:05:49.828Z","parentId":"2b9177b7-9343-441f-940f-163d05d059f9"}
